3. Regression Analysis: disability_employment vs employment_gap¶

Hypothesis:¶

The higher the number of disabled people unemployed, the higher the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people.

In [15]:
# Create a scatterplot using matplotlib to show disabled_employed and employment_gap.

employ.plot(x = 'disability_employed', y='employment_gap',style='o') 
plt.title('Number of Disabled People Employed Vs Employment Gap Between Disabled and Non-Disabled People')  
plt.xlabel('Percent of Disabled People Employed')  
plt.ylabel('Employment Gap Percent')  
plt.show()
In [16]:
# Reshape the variables into NumPy arrays and put them into separate objects.

X = employ['disability_employed'].values.reshape(-1,1)
y = employ['employment_gap'].values.reshape(-1,1)
In [19]:
# Split data into a training set and a test set.

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=0)
In [20]:
# Create a regression object.

regression = LinearRegression()
In [21]:
# Fit the regression object onto the training set.

regression.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[21]:
LinearRegression()
In a Jupyter environment, please rerun this cell to show the HTML representation or trust the notebook.
On GitHub, the HTML representation is unable to render, please try loading this page with nbviewer.org.
LinearRegression()
In [22]:
# Predict the values of y using X.

y_predicted = regression.predict(X_test)
In [23]:
# Create a plot that shows the regression line from the model on the test set.

plot_test = plt
plot_test.scatter(X_test, y_test, color='gray', s = 15)
plot_test.plot(X_test, y_predicted, color='red', linewidth =3)
plot_test.title('Number of Disabled People Employed Vs Employment Gap Between Disabled and Non-Disabled People (Test set)')
plot_test.xlabel('Percent of Disabled People Employed')
plot_test.ylabel('Employment Gap Percentage')
plot_test.show()

The line appears to fit the data well overall. There is a highly-concentrated area of data in the middle that might alter the results slightly, but even the dots that are not in that highly-concentrated area are close to the line.

In [24]:
# Create objects that contain the model summary statistics.

rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted) 
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_predicted)
In [25]:
# Print the model summary statistics. This is where you evaluate the performance of the model.

print('Slope:' ,regression.coef_)
print('Mean squared error: ', rmse)
print('R2 score: ', r2)

# Visualizing the training set results.

Overall, I think the model performed well on the test set. The R2 score is different by 0.05 and the MSE is different by 5. Both R2 scores are over 0.75 and both MSEs are under 25. This data could be more accurate if there were more data points.
